---

1. RC522 RFID Module (SPI Communication)

SDA → Raspberry Pi Pin 24 (GPIO 8, SPI CE0)

SCK → Raspberry Pi Pin 23 (GPIO 11, SPI Clock)

MOSI → Raspberry Pi Pin 19 (GPIO 10, SPI MOSI)

MISO → Raspberry Pi Pin 21 (GPIO 9, SPI MISO)

IRQ → Not connected (optional)

GND → Raspberry Pi Pin 6 (Ground)

RST → Raspberry Pi Pin 22 (GPIO 25)

3.3V → Raspberry Pi Pin 1 (3.3V Power)


✅ Note: Enable SPI using sudo raspi-config → Interfacing Options → SPI → Enable


---

2. IR Sensors (Entry & Exit Detection)

Entry IR Sensor Output → Raspberry Pi Pin 11 (GPIO 17)

Exit IR Sensor Output → Raspberry Pi Pin 13 (GPIO 27)

GND (both sensors) → Raspberry Pi Pin 6 (Ground)

VCC (both sensors) → Raspberry Pi Pin 2 (5V Power)



---

3. Servo Motor (Barrier Control)

Signal (PWM) → Raspberry Pi Pin 15 (GPIO 22)

VCC → External 5V power source (Do not power directly from Raspberry Pi)

GND → Raspberry Pi Ground (Pin 6)


✅ Note: Servo needs the pigpio library (sudo pigpiod must be running).


---

4. I2C LCD Display

SDA → Raspberry Pi Pin 3 (GPIO 2)

SCL → Raspberry Pi Pin 5 (GPIO 3)

VCC → Raspberry Pi Pin 2 (5V Power)

GND → Raspberry Pi Pin 6 (Ground)


✅ Note: Enable I2C using sudo raspi-config → Interfacing Options → I2C → Enable


---

5. Push Buttons (Add/Remove RFID Cards)

Add Card Button → Raspberry Pi Pin 29 (GPIO 5)

Remove Card Button → Raspberry Pi Pin 31 (GPIO 6)

GND (for both buttons) → Raspberry Pi Pin 6 (Ground)


✅ Note: Buttons use pull-up resistors in software (GPIO PULL_UP mode).


---

6. Power Connections

Raspberry Pi powered via USB-C or micro-USB adapter (depending on model).

Servo motor requires a separate 5V power supply to prevent power issues.

All ground connections (GND) should be linked together for a common ground.
